# Optical Constructor UI — feature list

This document is the free-form, prose-first description of what the
Optical Constructor user interface needs to become. It is *steering
prose*, not the structured spec: it captures who needs what and why,
the relative priority of each capability, and the open questions that
the spec-author and the operator still need to settle. The structured,
testable specification is written in the next step from this document.

A note on what already exists, so this list is read in context. The
project already has a working Avalonia + FuncUI (Elm-style MVU) desktop
application under `OpticalConstructor` with a dockable-panel main
screen (a Construction page and a Synthesis/Fit page), a *beam tree*
domain model (each non-mirror element splits light into a reflected and
a transmitted branch), a catalogue of element kinds (source, linear and
circular polarizer, sample, lens, flat and curved mirror, analyzer,
detector), JSON project files validated against a schema, canonical-SI
units with display-only conversion, and whole-project snapshot
undo/redo. This feature list does **not** restate that engine; it
describes the *new* operator-facing constructor screen that is layered
on top of it, and it reuses the existing physics, units, beam tree, and
storage rather than re-inventing them.

Throughout, relative priority is tagged with the MoSCoW convention —
**[Must]**, **[Should]**, **[Could]**, **[Won't-now]** — to help the
spec-author sequence the work. Terms specific to this project are
defined on first use and collected in the glossary at the end.

---

## 1. Main screen: ribbon-and-menu shell  [Must]

**Who / what / why.** The primary user is an optics researcher (often
the operator themselves) assembling and adjusting an optical experiment.
They need a main screen whose controls reorganise around the task in
hand, the way Microsoft Word and Excel do, so that the small set of
controls relevant *right now* is large and obvious, while everything
else stays one click away.

The desired behaviour, in plain terms:

- A **top menu bar** whose top-level entries each correspond to a
  **ribbon** — a horizontal band of task-relevant controls. Selecting a
  top-level menu entry switches the visible ribbon, exactly as clicking
  "Home", "Insert", "Layout" switches ribbons in Office.
- The ribbon is **collapsible**. When the ribbon is hidden to reclaim
  screen space, the same top menu entries expand into **full drop-down
  menus** that expose *everything* the ribbons offer. Nothing is
  reachable only through a ribbon and unreachable from the menus, or
  vice-versa — the two are two presentations of one command set. This
  single-source-of-commands property is the important part and should be
  designed so a new command is declared once and appears in both places
  automatically, rather than being wired up twice.
- A sensible default set of ribbon tabs, grouped by the phase of work —
  for example *Build* (place elements and groups), *Element* (edit the
  active element), *Trace / View* (rays, zoom, table view, reset),
  *Experiment* (groups, collections, detectors), and *Settings*
  (language, units, controls, help). The exact tab list is an open
  question for the spec-author to refine; see §13.

**Non-functional notes.** The ribbon must stay legible under EN and RU
strings, which differ in length (Cyrillic labels tend to run longer), so
the layout needs to flex rather than truncate. A *contextual* ribbon tab
for the active element is desirable (it appears when an element is
selected); good practice from comparable CAD tools is to **append**
contextual controls beside the persistent tabs rather than let a
contextual tab take over the whole ribbon.

**Reference for adjacent tools.** Office and CAD ribbon UIs commonly
offer three collapse states (full ribbon → titles-and-tabs → tabs only);
adopting that progression is a reasonable starting point but is a design
detail, not a fixed requirement here.

## 2. The legacy form  [Must]

**Who / what / why.** The current dockable-panel main screen is a good
illustration of what the application can already do, and the operator
wants to keep it reachable rather than discard it. The capability is: a
**"Legacy" menu entry** that opens the present main screen as-is, so the
existing panels, charts, fit page, and material tools remain available
while the new ribbon-based constructor becomes the front door. The
legacy form is a reference and a fallback, not something that needs to
evolve in lock-step with the new screen.

## 3. Languages: English and Russian  [Must]

**Who / what / why.** The user base spans English- and Russian-speaking
researchers, and the chosen language needs to persist between sessions.
The capability:

- Full **EN / RU** support across the interface, with the selected
  language **saved into settings** and restored on the next launch.
- All translatable string pairs live in **one centralized, human-
  editable resource** (a JSON, YAML, or similar text file) that is
  **read at run time**. An operator or translator can edit the strings,
  or add a further language, by editing that file — no rebuild required.
- At startup the application **checks the resource for completeness**.
  If any string is missing for the active language it **falls back to an
  English default** for that entry and surfaces a **startup error
  message the user can copy** (so it can be pasted into a bug report or
  a translation fix), rather than failing silently or crashing.

**Non-functional notes.** Scientific symbols and notation (Ψ, Δ, °, the
unit symbols, R1/R2/R3) stay language-neutral. This localization work is
new: prior specs treated localization as deferred, so the centralized
string resource and the startup completeness check are net-new
capabilities introduced here.

## 4. Standardized controls  [Must]

**Who / what / why.** As the interface grows, the maintainer needs
visual and behavioural consistency without hunting through the code for
every button. The capability is a **single place that describes the
standard control "flavours"** (the default button, a primary/accent
button, a destructive button, a toggle, a numeric field with units, and
so on). When a new flavour is genuinely needed — say a button in a
different colour to make it stand out — it is **added in that one place,
changing only the minimum set of properties** that distinguish it,
rather than being styled ad hoc at each call site. The goal is
consistency and one-touch restyling, not a comprehensive design system.

## 5. Units of measure  [Must, unchanged]

**Who / what / why.** Researchers work in whatever length unit suits the
quantity — metres down to ångströms, with inches available for those who
want them. The supported display units are **m, cm, mm, mkm (micron),
nm, Å, and in**, with values held internally in canonical SI and
converted only at the display and import/export boundary, and with each
element or source able to carry its own preferred display unit. This
matches what previous specs already settled; **there are no changes
here**, and this section exists only to record that the new screen
inherits that behaviour rather than redefining it.

## 6. The optical table (OT)  [Must]

**Definition.** The **optical table (OT)** is the working surface where
all editing happens — the canvas on which optical elements are placed
and the rays are drawn.

**Who / what / why.** The researcher needs a stable, top-down workspace
that behaves like looking down on a real optical bench, because the top
view is what an experiment is reasoned about in the great majority of
cases.

- **Default view is from the top**, and for most work that is all that
  is needed.
- **Left-press + drag on empty table** pans the whole table and every
  element on it together (the elements travel with the table).
- **Mouse wheel** (with no modifier) **zooms** in and out.
- The table itself can be **rotated as a view operation**: rotating the
  table only changes the viewpoint, so all elements "travel" with it.
  The table's own R1/R2/R3 are measured **relative to the screen**, and
  there is an **easy, one-action reset of the view back to (0, 0, 0)**
  (straight top-down). This reset is important because it is easy to
  tumble the view and hard to recover by hand.
- The **table is the selected object whenever the user clicks anything
  that is not an optical element**. Selecting the table is how the user
  steps "out of" an element to operate on the workspace as a whole.

**Non-functional notes.** Panning and zooming need to stay smooth as the
number of elements and rays grows; the rendering is a schematic, so it
does not need physical-grade ray accuracy to feel responsive.

## 7. Optical elements and their rotations  [Must]

**Definition.** An **optical element (OE)** is the basic unit placed on
the table. The **active element** is the one currently selected; **all
editing actions apply only to the active element**, and the active
element is drawn so that it is unmistakably the active one (a highlight,
halo, or selection frame — the exact treatment is a design detail, but
the *clarity* of it is a firm need, because acting on the wrong element
silently is the main hazard here).

**Three rotations.** Every element has three angles of rotation, always
measured **relative to the incident central ray** (see §8), not relative
to the screen:

- **R1** — rotation around the element's **primary normal**. The working
  interpretation to confirm with the operator: when the incident central
  ray is a horizontal line running left-to-right and the element faces
  that ray, R1 spins the element about that ray axis (for a polarizer,
  R1 is its azimuth). This is the interpretation this document assumes;
  see the open question in §13.
- **R2** — rotation around the **normal to the table** (the vertical
  axis in the top view). R2 is the tilt that steers a reflected beam in
  the plane of the table.
- **R3** — rotation around the **R1 × R2 axis**. R3 is very rarely used,
  is **locked by default**, and has to be deliberately unlocked before
  it can change.

**Showing and editing the angles.** Each element **displays its R1, R2,
R3 values nearby**. Clicking the displayed values lets the user **type
exact angles by hand**, and each rotation has its **own reset button**
(back to 0). The user can **lock or unlock any of the three rotations
individually**, freezing them at their current values to prevent
accidental change; R3 starts locked.

**Reset.** A single action (proposed **Shift+R, with confirmation**)
**resets the element to its standard orientation** (R1 = R2 = R3 = 0).

**Non-functional notes.** Because the rotations are always expressed
relative to the incident central ray, an element's stated angles stay
meaningful even after upstream elements have redirected the beam — that
invariance is part of why this model is worth the complexity.

## 8. The ray model: light, ray groups, and placement  [Must]

This section captures the physics-facing behaviour the constructor draws.
It is the conceptual heart of the tool and deserves careful treatment by
the spec-author.

**Light source and the ray group.** A **light source (LS)** emits a
**ray group (RG)** drawn as a small bundle of parallel lines: a
**central ray (CR)** plus **four side rays** — two left/right and two
top/bottom of the CR. Seen from the default top view, with no element
that spreads them, the top/bottom side rays coincide with the CR; the
side rays only visibly matter once **lenses, non-flat (curved) mirrors,
prisms, or wedges** bend them apart. The side rays exist so that
focusing, diverging, and dispersive behaviour can be shown
schematically.

**Reflected and transmitted ray groups.** Every element except a mirror
produces both a **transmitted ray group (TRG)** and a **reflected ray
group (RRG)**; a **mirror produces only an RRG**. Whether an element
emits R or T is **metadata on the element**: any element can be
configured to **ignore its reflected or its transmitted group, but never
both** — turning the second one off automatically turns the other one
back on. By default a mirror is placed with transmission off; every
other element is placed with whatever it is configured to suppress, if
anything.

**Incident light.** The light arriving at an element is its **incident
ray group (IRG)**; any ray group falling on an element is that element's
IRG. This is the frame against which the element's rotations are
measured.

**Photo detector terminates the ray.** A **photo detector (PD)**
**terminates the ray group** it receives. (The name "Photo Detector" is
flagged for confirmation — the existing model and common practice call
this simply a **Detector**; see §13.)

**Placement point and snapping.** Each element has a **placement point
(PP)** that **snaps onto the central ray (or onto its incident ray
group)**. When an element is rotated so that the ray group leaving it
changes direction, the downstream elements' placement points **travel
with the redirected central ray** — they re-snap onto the new path, and
their rotations re-anchor to the new incident central ray. In effect,
tilting one element drags everything downstream of it along the new beam
direction automatically. **Shift + left-press + drag** moves the active
element's placement point **along the central ray** (sliding it nearer
or further along the beam without leaving the beam).

**Schematic ray tracing through tilted elements.** When an element is
rotated such that R2 and/or R3 are non-zero, the beam genuinely changes
direction and the side rays may refract. The drawing is a **schematic**,
not a physical-optics render: it uses a **standard index of n = 1
outside and n = 1.5 inside** an element and applies **Snell's law** to
draw the bent lines. The exact conventions (how thick a schematic
element is, how the four side rays are offset, how reflection is drawn
when both R and T are on) are details for the spec-author to pin down;
the agreed principle is "schematic, Snell-based, n = 1 / n = 1.5".

**Relationship to the engine.** This CR-plus-side-rays drawing is the
visual layer; the quantitative result at each element still comes from
the existing Berreman beam-tree solver (reflected/transmitted branches),
so the schematic should stay consistent with which branches the engine
actually computes.

## 9. Standard element catalogue  [Must]

**Who / what / why.** Researchers think in terms of named bench
components, and the same role can be filled by different hardware (a
light source might be a green laser or a mercury lamp, but on the table
it is still "a light source"). The capability is a catalogue of
**standard element kinds**, named by their role on the table, with the
concrete device captured as a property of the element rather than as a
separate kind.

The proposed standard names (to be reviewed and completed):

- **Optical Table (OT)** — the workspace itself.
- **Light Source (LS)** — emits the ray group; the device (laser, lamp,
  wavelength/spectrum) is a property.
- **Linear Polarizer (LP)**.
- **Circular Polarizer (CP)**.
- **Sample (S)** — the material(s) under study.
- **Photo Detector (PD)** — terminates the ray (name under review).

The existing model also carries **lens, flat mirror, curved mirror, and
analyzer** element kinds. These should be reconciled into the catalogue:
in particular, a linear or circular polarizer placed *after* the sample
is playing the **analyzer** role of a polarizer–sample–analyzer chain,
which is worth naming explicitly so the user understands the setup.
Mirrors, lenses, prisms, and wedges are the elements that make the side
rays meaningful (§8) and are needed for focusing and dispersive setups.

## 10. Interaction model: mouse and keyboard  [Must]

**Who / what / why.** The researcher manipulates the active element and
the table mostly by mouse, with keyboard accelerators for speed. The
proposed scheme below is recorded together with this document's **advice
on each item**, since the operator explicitly asked for that review.
Every action operates on the **active element** unless it is a table
action.

Proposed scheme (operator's list, annotated):

- **Double-click** an element → open its **element dialog**. *Keep.*
- **Right-click** an element → context menu: element dialog, local help,
  and more. *Keep; suggested additions to the menu: lock/unlock each
  rotation, reset rotation, toggle reflected/transmitted, delete,
  duplicate, turn the element or its group on/off, and (for a detector)
  "set as primary".*
- **Ctrl+Z** undo, **Ctrl+Y** redo, with **more than one level**.
  *Keep; the underlying engine already supports multi-step undo. Suggest
  also accepting **Ctrl+Shift+Z** as a redo alias, which many users
  expect.*
- **Shift+R** (with confirmation) → reset the element's rotation to
  (0, 0, 0). *Keep.*
- **F1** → **local help**: a pop-up window describing the selected object
  and what its controls do. *Keep; see §12.*
- **Esc** → close the local menu / pop-up. *Keep; also a natural
  "cancel current drag / deselect" key.*
- **Left-press + drag on an element does nothing.** *Keep — this is a
  deliberate guard against accidental moves, which are very easy to
  trigger. The trade-off is discoverability: because the obvious gesture
  does nothing, the real gesture (Shift+drag) needs a visible hint, e.g.
  the cursor or a tooltip when the pointer is over a movable element.*
- **Shift + left-press + drag** → move the placement point **along the
  central ray**. *Keep.*
- **Shift + mouse wheel** → R1, default step **5°** (configurable), if
  not locked. *Keep.*
- **Ctrl + mouse wheel** → R2, step 5° (configurable), if not locked.
  *Keep, but flag a conflict: Ctrl+wheel is a very strong system-wide
  "zoom" convention. Since plain wheel already zooms the table, this is
  workable, but the operator should confirm Ctrl+wheel-as-R2 over the
  active element feels right; an alternative is to reserve plain wheel
  for zoom only and require the element to be active for any
  modifier+wheel rotation, which the scheme already implies.*
- **Alt + mouse wheel** → R3 (must be unlocked first), step 5°
  (configurable). *Keep.*

**Suggested additional hotkeys** (the operator asked for more where they
make sense):

- **Delete / Backspace** → remove the active element (with confirmation
  for a non-trivial element).
- **Ctrl+D** → duplicate the active element; **Ctrl+C / Ctrl+V** →
  copy/paste an element.
- **Tab / Shift+Tab** → make the next / previous element along the beam
  path active, so the whole chain can be stepped through without the
  mouse.
- **Arrow keys** → nudge the active element's placement point along the
  ray a small step; **Shift+arrow** for a larger step.
- **Ctrl+0** (or a "Reset view" button) → reset the table view to
  top-down (0, 0, 0) and a sensible zoom; **Ctrl+S** → save the project.
- **Number keys** → quickly toggle the corresponding element group on or
  off (ties into §11).

**Non-functional notes.** A consistent, discoverable scheme matters more
than any single binding; making the key map **configurable** (and the
rotation step already is) would let users resolve the Ctrl+wheel
question for themselves and is worth considering, though it can be a
later increment.

## 11. Element groups and experiment assembly  [Must]

**Definition.** An **element group** is one or more optical elements that
can be **placed onto, or removed from, the central-ray path as a unit**,
so the user can quickly assemble an experiment from chosen pieces.

**Who / what / why.** A researcher runs families of closely related
experiments — same beam, same detector, swapping one block at a time —
and needs to assemble and re-assemble them quickly rather than rebuild
from scratch. There is always a **primary central-ray path**; the groups
are the interchangeable blocks along it. A typical experiment reads as a
sequence of choices:

> LS ⇒ Group 1 (nothing, or LP1, or CP1) ⇒ Group 2 (nothing, or S1,
> or S2, or S1 + S2) ⇒ Group 3 (nothing, or LP2, or CP2) ⇒ PD

The capability is to **turn the elements of each group on and off
quickly** and to **swap the chosen piece** in each group, so a whole
experiment can be assembled, run, changed, and re-run as conditions
change. This makes the group the natural unit of "what is in the beam
right now". Groups should be nameable and reusable, building on the
existing favourites/board idea so a commonly used group can be pinned
and dropped back in later.

**Multiple detectors and the primary one.** The primary path normally
ends in one **photo detector**, but the user may place **more than one
PD** when a branch (e.g. a reflected arm) genuinely needs its own
detector. When there is more than one, the user **chooses which detector
is the primary one**; results and the headline readout follow the
primary detector, while secondary detectors report their own branch
independently.

## 12. Experiment collections  [Should]

**Definition.** An **experiment collection** is a set of experiments
built around the **same sample or samples** (the materials under study).

**Who / what / why.** A study of a given material produces many related
experiments, and the researcher wants them grouped so that elements and
groups can be turned on and off across the collection conveniently,
without losing the thread that ties them together (the shared sample).
The collection exists chiefly to make that on/off assembly convenient
across the related experiments, and to keep an experiment reproducible
when it has to be repeated because conditions changed.

## 13. Local help and onboarding  [Should]

**Who / what / why.** The interaction model above is rich, and a new
user (or a returning one) needs to learn what the controls of the
selected object do without leaving the table. The capability:

- **F1 / right-click → local help**: a pop-up describing the **selected
  object** and what each of its controls does — context-sensitive to the
  active element or to the table.
- Beyond that, light onboarding (tooltips, a short "what does this
  gesture do" hint for the deliberately-inert left-drag, a discoverable
  list of hotkeys) would meaningfully reduce the learning curve given
  how much behaviour is hidden behind modifier keys.

## 14. Undo, redo, and safety  [Must]

The constructor needs **multi-level undo and redo** across element
placement, rotation, locking, group on/off, and detector changes — not a
single step. The existing whole-project snapshot history already
provides multi-step undo/redo and should back this; the new screen's job
is to make sure every constructor action participates in it. Destructive
or hard-to-reverse actions (reset rotation, delete element, reset view)
should either be undoable or ask for confirmation, consistent with the
Shift+R-with-confirmation behaviour already proposed.

